\hypertarget{week-6-sliding-mode-control}{%
\section{Week 6: Sliding Mode Control}\label{week-6-sliding-mode-control}}

Variable Structure Control --- Robust Tracking Under Uncertainty

M.Sc. Control for Robots • AY 2025--26\\
Week 6 of 12 • Lecture + Hands-on MATLAB Lab

\hypertarget{week-7-recall-backstepping-control-exam-practice}{%
\subsection{Week 7 Recall: Backstepping Control --- Exam Practice}\label{week-7-recall-backstepping-control-exam-practice}}

\hypertarget{question-1-scalar-strict-feedback-system}{%
\subsubsection{Question 1 --- Scalar Strict-Feedback System}\label{question-1-scalar-strict-feedback-system}}

Consider the strict-feedback system:

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{x\}\_1 = x\_2 + x\_1\^{}2, \textbackslash qquad \textbackslash dot\{x\}\_2 = u.
\textbackslash{]}

\hypertarget{step-1-virtual-control-design}{%
\paragraph{Step 1 --- Virtual Control Design}\label{step-1-virtual-control-design}}

Define the first error variable:

\textbackslash{[} z\_1 = x\_1. \textbackslash{]}

Choose the first Lyapunov function:

\textbackslash{[} V\_1 = \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash,z\_1\^{}2. \textbackslash{]}

Its time derivative is:

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_1 = z\_1\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_1 = z\_1\textbackslash bigl(x\_2 + x\_1\^{}2\textbackslash bigr).
\textbackslash{]}

We want \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_1 = -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2\textbackslash) when \textbackslash(x\_2\textbackslash) equals a virtual control \textbackslash(\textbackslash alpha\_1(x\_1)\textbackslash). Setting

\textbackslash{[}
z\_1\textbackslash bigl(\textbackslash alpha\_1 + x\_1\^{}2\textbackslash bigr) = -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2
\textbackslash quad\textbackslash Longrightarrow\textbackslash quad
\textbackslash alpha\_1(x\_1) = -k\_1 x\_1 - x\_1\^{}2.
\textbackslash{]}

\hypertarget{step-2-actual-control-design}{%
\paragraph{Step 2 --- Actual Control Design}\label{step-2-actual-control-design}}

Define the second error variable:

\textbackslash{[} z\_2 = x\_2 - \textbackslash alpha\_1(x\_1). \textbackslash{]}

Note that \textbackslash(x\_2 = z\_2 + \textbackslash alpha\_1\textbackslash), so

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_1 = z\_1(z\_2 + \textbackslash alpha\_1 + x\_1\^{}2) = -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2 + z\_1 z\_2.
\textbackslash{]}

Augment the Lyapunov function:

\textbackslash{[} V\_2 = V\_1 + \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash,z\_2\^{}2 = \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}z\_1\^{}2 + \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}z\_2\^{}2. \textbackslash{]}

Differentiate \textbackslash(z\_2\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_2 = \textbackslash dot\{x\}\_2 - \textbackslash dot\{\textbackslash alpha\}\_1
= u - \textbackslash frac\{\textbackslash partial \textbackslash alpha\_1\}\{\textbackslash partial x\_1\}\textbackslash dot\{x\}\_1
= u - (-k\_1 - 2x\_1)(x\_2 + x\_1\^{}2).
\textbackslash{]}

Compute \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2 + z\_1 z\_2 + z\_2\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_2
= -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2 + z\_2\textbackslash bigl{[}z\_1 + u + (k\_1 + 2x\_1)(x\_2 + x\_1\^{}2)\textbackslash bigr{]}.
\textbackslash{]}

To obtain \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2 - k\_2 z\_2\^{}2\textbackslash), choose:

\textbackslash{[}
u = -z\_1 - k\_2 z\_2 - (k\_1 + 2x\_1)(x\_2 + x\_1\^{}2).
\textbackslash{]}

This yields \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = -k\_1 z\_1\^{}2 - k\_2 z\_2\^{}2 \textbackslash le 0\textbackslash), guaranteeing global asymptotic stability.

\hypertarget{question-2-2-dof-manipulator-backstepping}{%
\subsubsection{Question 2 --- 2-DOF Manipulator Backstepping}\label{question-2-2-dof-manipulator-backstepping}}

Given the manipulator dynamics \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash ddot\{q\} + C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash dot\{q\} + G(q) = \textbackslash tau\textbackslash), define:

\textbackslash{[}
z\_1 = q - q\_d, \textbackslash qquad
\textbackslash alpha\_1 = \textbackslash dot\{q\}\_d - K\_1 z\_1, \textbackslash qquad
z\_2 = \textbackslash dot\{q\} - \textbackslash alpha\_1.
\textbackslash{]}

Choose the composite Lyapunov function:

\textbackslash{[}
V\_2 = \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash,z\_1\^{}T z\_1 + \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash,z\_2\^{}T M(q)\textbackslash,z\_2.
\textbackslash{]}

Differentiate:

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = z\_1\^{}T \textbackslash dot\{z\}\_1 + z\_2\^{}T M(q)\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_2 + \textbackslash tfrac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash,z\_2\^{}T \textbackslash dot\{M\}(q)\textbackslash,z\_2.
\textbackslash{]}

Since \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_1 = \textbackslash dot\{q\} - \textbackslash dot\{q\}\_d = z\_2 + \textbackslash alpha\_1 - \textbackslash dot\{q\}\_d = z\_2 - K\_1 z\_1\textbackslash), we get:

\textbackslash{[}
z\_1\^{}T \textbackslash dot\{z\}\_1 = -z\_1\^{}T K\_1 z\_1 + z\_1\^{}T z\_2.
\textbackslash{]}

For the second term, note \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_2 = \textbackslash ddot\{q\} - \textbackslash dot\{\textbackslash alpha\}\_1\textbackslash), and from the dynamics \textbackslash(M\textbackslash ddot\{q\} = \textbackslash tau - C\textbackslash dot\{q\} - G\textbackslash), so:

\textbackslash{[}
M\textbackslash dot\{z\}\_2 = \textbackslash tau - C\textbackslash dot\{q\} - G - M\textbackslash dot\{\textbackslash alpha\}\_1.
\textbackslash{]}

Using the skew-symmetry property \textbackslash(z\_2\^{}T(\textbackslash dot\{M\} - 2C)z\_2 = 0\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = -z\_1\^{}T K\_1 z\_1 + z\_1\^{}T z\_2 + z\_2\^{}T\textbackslash bigl{[}\textbackslash tau - C\textbackslash dot\{q\} - G - M\textbackslash dot\{\textbackslash alpha\}\_1 + C z\_2\textbackslash bigr{]}.
\textbackslash{]}

Simplifying \textbackslash(-C\textbackslash dot\{q\} + Cz\_2 = -C(\textbackslash dot\{q\} - z\_2) = -C\textbackslash alpha\_1\textbackslash), so:

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = -z\_1\^{}T K\_1 z\_1 + z\_2\^{}T\textbackslash bigl{[}z\_1 + \textbackslash tau - C\textbackslash alpha\_1 - G - M\textbackslash dot\{\textbackslash alpha\}\_1\textbackslash bigr{]}.
\textbackslash{]}

Choose the backstepping torque:

\textbackslash{[}
\textbackslash tau = M\textbackslash dot\{\textbackslash alpha\}\_1 + C\textbackslash alpha\_1 + G - z\_1 - K\_2 z\_2
\textbackslash{]}

which yields \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{V\}\_2 = -z\_1\^{}T K\_1 z\_1 - z\_2\^{}T K\_2 z\_2 \textbackslash le 0\textbackslash).

\hypertarget{learning-outcomes}{%
\subsection{Learning Outcomes}\label{learning-outcomes}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Understand the two phases of sliding mode control: the \textbf{reaching phase} (driving the state to the sliding surface) and the \textbf{sliding phase} (reduced-order dynamics on \textbackslash(s=0\textbackslash)); derive the \textbf{equivalent control}.
\item
  Design \textbf{sliding surfaces} for second-order systems and multi-DOF robots: choose surface parameters \textbackslash(\textbackslash lambda\textbackslash) or \textbackslash(\textbackslash Lambda\textbackslash) to assign desired closed-loop error dynamics.
\item
  Derive complete SMC laws for three robotic platforms: \textbf{manipulator}, \textbf{mobile robot}, and \textbf{quadrotor drone}.
\item
  Analyse and mitigate the \textbf{chattering problem} using the boundary layer approach (\textbackslash(\textbackslash operatorname\{sat\}(s/\textbackslash varphi)\textbackslash)), and the \textbf{super-twisting algorithm}.
\item
  Implement SMC in \textbf{MATLAB/Simulink}, inject disturbances, and compare performance against computed torque, robust control, and backstepping.
\end{itemize}

